5 STATE OF MAINE
6 HOUSE OF REPRESENTATIVES
7 132ND LEGISLATURE
8 FIRST SPECIAL SESSION
9 COMMITTEE AMENDMENT “ ” to H.P. 982, L.D. 1498, “An Act to Limit
10 Municipal Impact Fees on Housing Development”
11 Amend the bill by striking out the title and substituting the following:
12 'An Act to Address Maine’s Housing Crisis by Limiting Municipal Impact Fees on
13 Housing Development and Transferring Oversight of the Housing Opportunity
14 Program to the Maine Office of Community Affairs'
15 Amend the bill by inserting after the title and before the enacting clause the following:
16 'Emergency preamble. Whereas, acts and resolves of the Legislature do not
17 become effective until 90 days after adjournment unless enacted as emergencies; and
18 Whereas, the State is facing a severe housing crisis, and to meet the goal of building
19 an additional 84,000 homes in the next 5 years to alleviate this crisis, housing production
20 in the State would need to roughly double its annual rate; and
21 Whereas, an array of changes needs to occur to address this crisis, starting with the
22 consolidation of efforts by the executive branch in this area; and
23 Whereas, transferring oversight of the Housing Opportunity Program from the
24 Department of Economic and Community Development is one critical component in
25 focusing the State's efforts addressing this crisis; and
26 Whereas, delaying consolidation of efforts will further delay implementation of new
27 and ongoing legislative initiatives enacted in this Legislature and in the 131st Legislature;
28 and
29 Whereas, in the judgment of the Legislature, these facts create an emergency within
30 the meaning of the Constitution of Maine and require the following legislation as
31 immediately necessary for the preservation of the public peace, health and safety; now,
32 therefore,'
33 Amend the bill by inserting after the enacting clause and before section 1 the following:
Page 1 - 132LR2143(02)
COMMITTEE AMENDMENT

COMMITTEE AMENDMENT “ ” to H.P. 982, L.D. 1498
1 'Sec. 1. 5 MRSA §3205, as enacted by PL 2023, c. 643, Pt. DD, §2, is amended to
2 read:
3 §3205. Acceptance and administration of funds
4 The office may accept, administer and expend funds, including but not limited to funds
5 from the Federal Government or from private sources, for purposes consistent with this
6 chapter. The director shall provide a report of the amount of any outside funding received
7 from private sources and its designated purpose to the Governor, the joint standing
8 committee of the Legislature having jurisdiction over housing matters and the joint
9 standing committee of the Legislature having jurisdiction over municipal matters on an
10 annual basis.
11 Sec. 2. 5 MRSA c. 310-C is enacted to read:
12 CHAPTER 310-C
13 HOUSING PLANNING
14 §3217. Housing Opportunity Program
15 1. Program established; administration. The Housing Opportunity Program,
16 referred to in this section as "the program," is established within the Maine Office of
17 Community Affairs, established in section 3202 and referred to in this section as "the
18 office." The program must encourage and support the development of additional housing
19 units in the State, including housing units that are affordable for low-income and moderate-
20 income individuals and housing units targeted to community workforce housing needs. The
21 office shall administer the program and provide technical and financial assistance to
22 support communities implementing zoning and land use-related policies necessary to
23 support increased housing development. The program must support regional approaches
24 and municipal model ordinance development and encourage policies that support increased
25 housing density, where feasible, to protect working lands and natural lands.
26 2. Housing Opportunity Fund. The Housing Opportunity Fund, referred to in this
27 section as "the fund," is established as a fund within the office for the purpose of providing
28 funds for the program. The fund consists of money appropriated to the fund by the
29 Legislature and any funds received by the office for the purposes of the program.
30 A. The office shall solicit applications for grants from the fund through a competitive
31 application process. Grants may be awarded to experienced service providers and
32 municipalities to:
33 (1) Support municipal ordinance development, provide technical assistance and
34 encourage public participation and community engagement in the process of
35 increasing housing opportunities;
36 (2) Provide community housing planning services to municipalities to support the
37 creation of housing development plans, including municipal ordinances, and policy
38 amendments to support those plans; and
39 (3) Provide community housing implementation services.
Page 2 - 132LR2143(02)
COMMITTEE AMENDMENT

COMMITTEE AMENDMENT “ ” to H.P. 982, L.D. 1498
1 Programs receiving grants under subparagraph (1) may encourage regional
2 coordination between municipalities.
3 Grants awarded must be for a period of up to 3 years, with required progress reports
4 each year.
5 B. The office shall provide technical assistance, housing policy development and
6 guidance directly to regional groups, municipalities and other housing stakeholders, to
7 the extent feasible with available resources. This may include, but is not limited to,
8 assisting municipalities with information about available grant opportunities, sharing
9 best practices from jurisdictions inside and outside of the State, providing model
10 language for municipal ordinances and policies and providing information to the
11 general public, which may support local and statewide policy changes meant to
12 increase the supply of housing.
13 3. Program evaluation. A recipient of grant funds through the program shall
14 cooperate with the office in performing evaluations and specific reporting requirements.
15 4. Rulemaking. The office may establish by rule the criteria for eligibility for grants
16 from the program and the process for applying to the program. Rules adopted pursuant to
17 this subsection are routine technical rules as defined in Title 5, chapter 375, subchapter 2-
18 A.
19 Sec. 3. 5 MRSA §13056-J, as enacted by PL 2021, c. 635, Pt. U, §1, is repealed.'
20 Amend the bill by striking out all of section 2 and inserting the following:
21 'Sec. 2. 30-A MRSA §4354, sub-§1, as amended by PL 1999, c. 776, §11, is further
22 amended to read:
23 1. Construction or fees may be required. The requirements may include
24 construction of capital infrastructure improvements or impact fees instead of capital
25 infrastructure improvements including the expansion or replacement of existing
26 infrastructure facilities and the construction of new infrastructure facilities. A municipality
27 shall demonstrate that a required infrastructure improvement is necessary to accommodate
28 the development and that the impact fee is based on the cost of the infrastructure
29 improvement and proportionate to the development's use of the infrastructure
30 improvement.
31 A. For the purposes of this subsection, infrastructure facilities include, but are not
32 limited to:
33 (1) Waste water collection and treatment facilities;
34 (2) Municipal water facilities;
35 (3) Solid waste facilities;
36 (4) Public safety equipment and facilities;
37 (5) Roads and traffic control devices;
38 (6) Parks and other open space or recreational areas; and
39 (7) School facilities.'
40 Amend the bill in section 3 in paragraph C in the 2nd line (page 1, line 26 in L.D.) by
41 striking out the following: "use" and inserting the following: 'use encumber'
